node.text:
We are proud to announce the launch of The Dogist Fund, our new philanthropic giving initiative. The Dogist is committed to the greater good of the entire dog community, and The Dogist Fund will serve this important mission in new ways. The Dogist Fund will empower non-profit work worldwide in the areas of dog rescue, rehabilitation, and working dogs – 100% of the funds raised will be put towards these programs.

When The Dogist first began in 2013, we introduced ‘Give a Dog a Bone’, a program that allowed our audience to sponsor individual adoptable dogs. Then in 2019, after launching The Dogist Shop, we introduced ‘Feeding Friends’, which donated 20,091 meals to rescue dogs in need. Additionally, through social media campaigns and rescue rides, we have helped find homes for more than 1,000 dogs and raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for animal rescue causes worldwide.

The Dogist Fund will take our charitable giving to the next level with a more comprehensive and intentional approach to canine welfare. By harnessing the power of our partners, our large dog-loving community, as well as being supported by a portion of our own bottom line, we know the fund will have a meaningful impact for the wellbeing of dogs individually and at large. We hope you will join us in supporting The Dogist Fund initiative as we develop it and help dogs and their people live better lives together around the world! To learn more about The Dogist Fund, or to make a donation, visit the link in our bio.

They walked me right into her.  We have a shared love of dogs in common. We have to love dogs like they love us, and feed them good, fresh food. And be patient. Always patient.” • A special series in partnership with @thefarmersdog

node.text: FUNDRAISING: Jose & Josette, German Shepherd (3 y/o), Working guide dog team from @guidingeyes, NY • “She’s my first guide dog. In 2010 I was diagnosed with retinitis pigmentosa, a progressive genetic condition, and in 2017 it progressed rapidly and I was deemed legally blind. My family encouraged me to apply for a guide dog and came across Guiding Eyes. They were so helpful through the process and I was placed with Josette in November, 2020. I didn’t know what to expect, honestly. I had to learn the commands and it took about a week into the training to gain confidence, but then it was like back to the way it was before my vision loss. I was going out more at night, all the way across town in the middle of the night. We went though one of the busiest streets and it was emotional for me. Everything that she navigated me through. The trust in her to guide me. Working together. The possibility of going to any new place. We’re going to do the upcoming Wagathon walk and she’s going to be Best Woman at my wedding.” • Join Team Dogist in this year’s Wag-A-Thon! The Wag-A-Thon is a cumulative marathon that you and your dog can do anywhere, at your own pace over the month of September. The goal is to hit 26.2 miles by September 30 – all while raising critical funds to support Guiding Eyes for the Blind’s mission to provide guide dogs to people with vision loss. For more information about how to get involved or to support our team, head to the link in bio!

node.text: ADOPTABLE: Bella, Bedlington Terrier mix (5 y/o), New York, NY• “Bella is gaining confidence in her wheels every day. She’s never known anything other than the way she used to get around, which is not good for her back. We’ve slowly had to convince her that this is a good idea. It’s been two weeks since she got her wheelchair. She’s obsessed with her raw diet so it’s been a useful tool for us to motivate her to practice her mobility. She’s gotten very good at running over toes and getting her wheels stuck on every corner she passes. Bella is our 29th foster and the perfect house guest. She’s extremely people and dog friendly and loves to greet everyone she sees. She’s an expert snuggler and if you look like you’re even thinking about giving her a belly rub, she will drop to your feet and roll over. Her older foster brother is hard to win over and is quite a grouch, but she’s touched his curmudgeon heart and won him over quickly. She has that effect on everyone.” • We cannot thank you all enough for helping us raise $10K for Bella’s transport, rehabilitation & long term care. We’re so happy to announce that she is now AVAILABLE for adoption! If Bella has stolen your heart (like she has with us) contact @truenorthrescuemission to apply to adopt!

node.text: Bella gets a physical assessment and does her first water therapy session at @water4dogsnyc, New York, NY • “The pool is basically a zero-g environment for her, and at a 90-degree temperature. Water therapy helps with circulation and flexibility of the joints and increases range of motion comfortably. We’re trying to get her to stretch and use her muscles as much as possible to move the joint fluid and help nutrients circulate through the joint. To have her be as active as possible, we try to judge the length of time in the pool to their ability to swim, like one-minute swims with breaks in your arms. Most of our clients have conditions that will improve, and with Bella we’re trying to increase her comfort as much as possible. She won’t entirely heal, but this will help . We’re trying to give her a break from gravity and use her full body as best she can.” • For more information about Bella and The Dogist Fund, head to the link in bio!

node.text: Barry (& his new family), Schnauzer mix (3 y/o), Clinton & Atlantic Ave., Brooklyn, NY • Barry was rescued from Harbin, China, via @slaughterhouse_survivors & @truenorthrescuemission • Along with Bella, Barry was rescued before the CDC travel ban went into place on July 14th, preventing dogs from traveling to and from over 100 countries, including China. • "We waited for Barry for six months and scoured the rescue site for him. We had seen him in videos at the safehouse in China. Our son wanted a dog to play fetch with and our daughter wanted one to cuddle. Barry loves to do both – he’s better than we could have imagined. He is the quintessential New Yorker – walks at a fast pace but stops to check out every other human and dog. Overall his adjustment to city life has been pretty seamless. He’s unfazed by construction on our street. He loves a belly rub and his favorite place is lying between us in bed on his back with his paws up. Sometimes he falls asleep like that. He does not like the heat and humidity. When we go to walk him he hides under a chair. He also hates vacuums."

node.text: John Snow, Rosa, Jenny, Rachel, and Louise – 5 dogs rescued from Harbin, China, via @slaughterhouse_survivors, @atlasanimalrescue & @truenorthrescuemission • Along with Bella, these five dogs were rescued before the CDC travel ban went into place on July 14th, preventing dogs from traveling to and from over 100 countries, including China. • “John was rescued with five other Alaskan Malamutes from a life of abuse. They were owned by a Chinese ski resort and were used as a sled dog tourist attraction. When they were first rescued, they had scars on their faces and one had a broken leg. It was alleged that when business was slow they would sell them to the meat trade, an unfortunately common fate for dogs in the region. You would never imagine that’s where Jon came from when you meet him today. He is the happiest, sweetest giant floof, and now enjoys retirement on the beach in Santa Barbara, California.” For more information about these pups and their adoptability, head to @atlasanimalrescue & @truenorthrescuemission!

node.text: Bella, Bedlington Terrier mix (5 y/o), LAX, Los Angeles, CA • Meet the first recipient of The Dogist Fund! This sweet girl is a pup with special needs, rescued in Harbin, China by @Slaughterhouse_Survivors and with our help, was transported to the U.S. by @truenorthrescuemission. She was one of the last few pups to be imported before the CDC’s travel ban went into effect on 7/14, prohibiting dogs from traveling to and from 113 countries, including China. As you can imagine, this has been devastating for rescue organizations such as Slaughterhouse Survivors who dedicate their lives to rescuing dogs from dire situations. Our team flew out to LA in July to transport Bella to her foster home in NYC. Upon her arrival in New York, Bella was diagnosed with bilateral angular deformity of femurs with luxation of the stifle and tarsi. This means she has a malformation of her hips, therefore compromising mobility in her back legs. To prevent her from dragging her back legs, Bella will require the use of a wheelchair and ongoing physical therapy. Please join us in raising $10K to cover Bella's transport, rehabilitation & long-term care. For more information on how to donate to Bella’s care and towards future recipients of The Dogist Fund, head to the link in our bio.

node.text:
We are proud to announce the launch of The Dogist Fund, our new philanthropic giving initiative. The Dogist is committed to the greater good of the entire dog community, and The Dogist Fund will serve this important mission in new ways. The Dogist Fund will empower non-profit work worldwide in the areas of dog rescue, rehabilitation, and working dogs – 100% of the funds raised will be put towards these programs.

When The Dogist first began in 2013, we introduced ‘Give a Dog a Bone’, a program that allowed our audience to sponsor individual adoptable dogs. Then in 2019, after launching The Dogist Shop, we introduced ‘Feeding Friends’, which donated 20,091 meals to rescue dogs in need. Additionally, through social media campaigns and rescue rides, we have helped find homes for more than 1,000 dogs and raised hundreds of thousands of dollars for animal rescue causes worldwide.

The Dogist Fund will take our charitable giving to the next level with a more comprehensive and intentional approach to canine welfare. By harnessing the power of our partners, our large dog-loving community, as well as being supported by a portion of our own bottom line, we know the fund will have a meaningful impact for the wellbeing of dogs individually and at large. We hope you will join us in supporting The Dogist Fund initiative as we develop it and help dogs and their people live better lives together around the world! To learn more about The Dogist Fund, or to make a donation, visit the link in our bio.

node.text: Luna, Alaskan Malamute/Husky mix (8 y/o), Eastern Promenade, Portland, ME • “You have to spell things. ‘Ice cream’ has to be spelled. She even understands my Hindi. She knows ‘chalo’, which means ‘let’s go’. She understands ‘Do you want love?’ – she falls down and is like, ‘Ok love me’. She can not be let off the leash. She’ll run zip codes. Lots of legs will cover lots of ground. It’s the Husky in her. Her motto, like the New Hampshire state motto, is ‘Live Free or Die’.”

node.text: Kilo, Pit Bull/Husky mix (1 y/o), Quarry Run Dog Park, Portland, ME • “She doesn’t do anything that’s wet. She bunny-hops over puddles and doesn’t like baths; terrified of snow. She’s completely deaf, so it makes everything a little intimidating to her. Normally when we’re out and about I use the vibrate collar – that’s how I call her. She also knows how to roll down the windows of the car and knows that the front windows aren’t locked. If I’m at a store, she’ll roll them down, jump out and come inside. She’s really smart. Sometimes I wish she wasn’t that smart. It gets a little scary sometimes. She was found as a puppy in a closet in an abandoned apartment with four of her siblings.”
